
[1]drench

   DRENCH, v.t. [G., to water, to soak. See Drink and Drag.]

   1. To wet thoroughly; to soak; to fill or cover with water or other
   liquid; as garments drenched in rain or in the sea; the flood has
   drenched the earth; swords drenched in blood.

   2. To saturate with drink.

   3. To purge violently.

    DRENCH, n. A draught; a swill; also, a portion of medicine to purge a
     beast, particularly a horse. Hence, a violent dose of physic to be
                           forced down the throat.
